gland","Spencer Combe, Devon, England":"Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Spencer","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Yorkshire): occupational name for someone who dispensed provisions or money, from Middle English <i>spenser(e)</i>, <i>spencer(e)</i> ‘household steward, butler, almoner’ (Anglo-Norman French <i>espenser</i>, Old French <i>despensier</i>). Compare   Spence   and   Spender  . There is some dispute about the origins of the Spencer family, whose most famous member in recent times was the late Princess of Wales, born Lady Diana Spencer (1961–97). Some sources say that they are descended from William the Conqueror's steward, Robert Despencer. What is clear is that by the 15th century they had become prosperous from sheep farming in Northamptonshire. Robert Spencer (died 1627) was said to be the wealthiest man in England. Their titles have included Earls of Sunderland and Earls Spencer; and through the female line the 5th Earl of Sunderland also became Duke of Marlborough in 1733. This connection was the result of the marriage, in 1700, of the 3rd Duke of Sunderland to the daughter of John Churchill, 1st Duke of Marlborough. The youngest son of this union, John Spencer (1708–46), was the father of the 1st Earl Spencer (1734–83)."],"variants":[{"name":"Spence","meanings":["English and Scottish: nickname for a servant employed in the pantry of a great house or monastery, from Middle English <i>spense</i>, <i>spence</i> ‘pantry, larder, storeroom’ (Old French <i>despense</i>, from a Late Latin derivative of <i>dispendere</i>, past participle <i>dispensus</i> ‘to weigh out or dispense’). Compare   Spencer  ."]},{"name":"Spenser","meanings":["English: variant of   Spencer  ."]},{"name":"Spender","meanings":["English:","occupational name or status name from Middle English <i>spender(e)</i>, <i>spendour</i> ‘steward, treasurer’, a shortened form of Middle English, Old French <i>despendour</i>, denoting someone who managed money or supplies. Compare   Spencer  .","alternatively, perhaps a nickname from Middle English <i>spender(e)</i>, <i>spendour</i> ‘spender (of money), spendthrift’."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":20,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Robert Spencer of Spencer Combe was born in 1435, in Devon, England, his father, John Spencer, was 30 and his mother, Joan, was 25. He married Eleanor Beaufort in 1465, in England. They were the parents of at least 2 daughters. He died in 1510, in Devon, England, at the age of 75."},"et":{"1435–1510":"1435–1510","1431–1501":"1431–1501","1472–1536":"1472–1536","1477–1542":"1477–1542","1405–Male":"1405–Surnud","1410–Female":"1410–Surnud","1472":"1472","1536":"1536","1435":"1435","1501":"1501","1477":"1477","1510":"1510","1455":"1455","1465":"1465","1410":"1410","1542":"1542","1431":"1431","16 August 1501":"16. august 1501","1405":"1405","Spencercombe, Devon, England":"Devon, England","Spencercombe (Devonshire) England":"Devon, England","England":"England","Spencer Combe, Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"fi":{"1435–1510":"1435–1510","1431–1501":"1431–1501","1472–1536":"1472–1536","1477–1542":"1477–1542","1405–Male":"1405–Kuollut","1410–Female":"1410–Kuollut","1472":"1472","1536":"1536","1435":"1435","1501":"1501","1477":"1477","1510":"1510","1455":"1455","1465":"1465","1410":"1410","1542":"1542","1431":"1431","16 August 1501":"16. elokuuta 1501","1405":"1405","Spencercombe, Devon, England":"Devon, England","Spencercombe (Devonshire) England":"Devon, England","England":"England","Spencer Combe, Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"fr":{"1435–1510":"1435–1510","1431–1501":"1431–1501","1472–1536":"1472–1536","1477–1542":"1477–1542","1405–Male":"1405–Décédé","1410–Female":"1410–Décédée","1472":"1472","1536":"1536","1435":"1435","1501":"1501","1477":"1477","1510":"1510","1455":"1455","1465":"1465","1410":"1410","1542":"1542","1431":"1431","16 August 1501":"16 août 1501","1405":"1405","Spencercombe, Devon, England":"Devon, Angleterre","Spencercombe (Devonshire) England":"Devon, Angleterre","England":"Angleterre","Spencer Combe, Devon, England":"Devon, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Sir Robert Spencer of Spencer Combe est né en 1435, à Devon, Angleterre, son père, John Spencer, avait 30 ans et sa mère, Joan, avait 25 ans. Il a épousé Eleanor Beaufort en 1465, à Angleterre. Ils ont eu au moins 2 filles. Il est décédé en 1510, à Devon, Angleterre, à l’âge de 75 